The abundance of choice and the ease of access usually brings in users who sign up precisely for those reasons vs actual interest. You might want to discount for that and/or try putting an entry barrier like a test/price to filter in the truly interested ones.
These beginner level IoT projects can be built in just 30 minuits. https:// hubs.ly/H0dDFmh0

Hi. Usually the reasons for this are : 1) Lack of time for the user to pursue, as other things have started to take up that time or mind-space 2) After the initial romance or interest, it has died down 3) It is free or heavily subsidized and hence the user has de-prioritized it

I'd agree with @sagarkamat that it is distractions. Ill begin a course, stumble upon a part not covered, move to another material that covers that part and that sometimes becomes an endless overwhelming loop that you completely diverge away from the course. Happens to me.
@sagarkamat Thanks for that insight. Hopefully I will get to hear from more people.

personally, for me, distraction. I am increasingly frustrated with my lack of focus and personal discipline to see various endeavors to their logical end. Trying hard to change this. True for exercising, learning and projects.
That is true. Even with the video training of @boltiot we have seen this happen. Working hard to solve it. Check https:// twitter.com/ppv999/status/ 1038283794661367813 …
